Generate a lifelike video animation from the provided image. The camera is fixed and stationary.

The subject must rotate only their head in an exceptionally slow, smooth, and biologically realistic motion, completing exactly one full left-to-center-to-right-to-center cycle (do not stop after turning left; do not end off-center):

1) Start perfectly centered (head facing forward).
2) Gently turn the head LEFT to exactly 70 degrees from center (hard stop at 70°: do not exceed 70° and do not stop short—must reach the full 70° before reversing). The turn is yaw-only (no tilt or nod), with absolutely no movement in the shoulders, neck position, torso, or upper body, which must stay perfectly upright and still.
3) Hold a brief, natural pause at the leftmost 70° position, then gently return smoothly back to exact center and hold a brief natural pause at center.
4) Gently turn the head RIGHT to exactly 70 degrees from center (same hard stop at 70°: not more, not less), maintaining the same extremely slow and continuous, lifelike pace.
5) Hold a brief, natural pause at the rightmost 70° position, then gently return smoothly back to exact center and finish centered (final frame must be centered).

Head motion must appear completely natural, never robotic, mechanical, stiff, or artificial—mimic genuine human motion with soft micro-adjustments and subtle ease-in/ease-out. Eyes stay focused on the camera lens through the entire sequence. Facial expression remains strictly neutral and relaxed throughout.

Lighting on the face and background must stay natural, matching the original image, with no added highlights, shadows, flicker, exposure changes, or artificial lighting. Only the head moves; the rest of the body remains motionless.
